snippet.textDisplay:
To the folks claiming this looks stupid or too much like Stranger Things instead of like Ghostbusters, just remember: Jumanji Welcome to the Jungle.

How many of us remember seeing the first trailer for JWttJ and thought it looked “stupid” and “not like a Jumanji movie” because of the video game angle it went with, only to be pleasantly surprised that the final product not only did its own thing, but was a direct sequel to the Robin Williams original that paid its proper respects to that film?

I am keeping the hope that Ghostbusters Afterlife is much the same: A sequel that does its own thing but still pays its proper respects to the beloved original.

snippet.textDisplay:
The 2016 version was a remake that ignored the first two movies, they chose to not be a part of this franchise. It's true that there hasn't been any Ghostbusters for 30 years. If, in 2016, they had made one of the characters a granddaughter of one of the original Ghostbusters who wanted to continue in the family business, and she brought in three of her girlfriends to help her, I would have been interested. Of course, if they had still made every single male character a pathetic negative feminist stereotype, in order to make the female leads look clever in contrast, I wouldn't have liked it. The sexist hatred in this scenario was definitely from those who wrote, produced, and directed that bomb.
I'm excited for Ghostbusters 3, the franchise deserves this level of respect and affection. And I'm also sure it will be much less sexist than the 2016 remake.

The sexist hatred in this scenario was definitely from those who wrote, produced, and directed that bomb.
